Cell.Data: External Identifier associated with this element
External Identifiers associated with this element - these are identifiers that are associated with the concept this element represents
Identifiers can appear anywhere people want them
What is the date of the patient's birth?
Prompt for element phrased as question
The default/suggested phrasing to use when prompting a human to capture the data element in question form (e.g. In a survey)

Question and label serve similar purposes in they both can be used to prompt for capturing a data element. Whether the question form or label form should be used will depend on the type of instrument being used to capture the information. The ordering is in order of preference. I.e. Most preferred question form is listed first. Note that this is for alternate phrasings of the question. Language translations are handled using the ISO 21090 string translation extensions.
Add "What is the date of the patient's birth?" as an example when tooling is fixed
Units to use for measured value
Identifies the units of measure in which the element should be captured or expressed.
Use a value set if more than one unit of measure is possible. Value sets will typically be short enough to display in a drop-down selection list.

The maximum allowable value set, for use when the binding strength is 'extensible' or 'preferred'. This value set is the value set from which additional codes can be taken from. This defines a 'required' binding over the top of the extensible binding
Typically, this will be an entire code system, e.g. SNOMED CT. The maximum binding needs to include all the codes in the extensible or preferred binding
Minimum Value Set (what system must support)
The minimum allowable value set, for use when the binding strength is 'required' or 'extensible'. This value set is the minimum value set that any conformant system SHALL support
Generally, the context of use of this extension should be specific about what it means to 'support' the value set
An extensible Value Set specified in a parent profile

A reference to an extensible value set specified in a parent profie in order to allow a conformance checking tool to validate that a code not in the extensible value set of the profile is not violating rules defined by parent profile bindings

This extension is only needed where the binding strength is 'extensible', the parents are also 'extensible'. This allows a validator to work around the fact that restricting extensible value sets in child profiles loses constraints out of the parent profiles, (e.g. codes to be used when appropriate)
A name that can be used for code generation when generating named enumerations for the binding
There is no need to use this name for conformance to the specification, but implementers may prefer to match e.g. the schema enumeration name
Whether the binding is used on multiple resources, or only on this resource

Some bindings are defined once internally and used in many places. This extension marks those bindings, to allow for generating the binding information once when generating code. When isCommonBinding is true, bindingName will be the same, and unique (e.g. identify re-uses by looking at bindingName)
equivalent | equal | wider | subsumes | narrower | specializes | inexact | unmatched | disjoint
The level of equivalence between the element containing the mapping and the element mapped to
Use this extension to indicate tha the element has an XML namespace different to http://hl7.org/fhir
If this is specified in a structure definition (logical models only), every element has the specified namespace
Mark a warning invariant as 'best practice'
Mark that an invariant represents 'best practice' rule - a rule that implementers may choose to enforce at error level in some or all circumstances
Validators may/should offer implementers the choice to enforce invariants labeled as 'best practice' as errors not warnings
Explains why an invariant is labelled as best practice
Explains why an invariant is labelled as a best practice invariant
FHIRPath that defines the selection criteria for a slice
A FHIRPath statement that defines whether an element is in the slice

This extension can only appear on element definitions that are part of a set of slices, and not on the slicing definition itself. If the selector appears in the presence of nominated slices discriminators, then the slicing defined by the discriminator(s) and the selector on each slice must agree. In the absence of any nominated discriminators, then an element is allowed to be in multiple slices
Whether translations apply to this element
Whether translations might be expected for this element in resource instances
This is a hint to design tools (e.g. profile editors, UI builders) that translations are likely to be appropriate for this element in countries that are multi-lingual
An additional binding that indicates that additional codes are required in addition to the main binding
Typical Use cases revolve around transition from on code system to another, so a resoruce must contain both codes during the transition period
This is only to be used on CodeableConcepts. For each additional binding specified, the CodeableConcept SHALL contain a code that meets the binding
A description of why this additional binding is present
Points to the value set or external definition (e.g. implicit value set) that identifies the set of codes to be used
The reference may be version-specific or not
Specific element for profile (for backbone elements)
The specific element to use in the referenced profile. This is used when a backbone element is being profiled, rather than an established type
The backbone element cannot be the root of the struture definition, so the starting element must be specified separately
A pattern that the target resources follow
A pattern that all the target resources follow - that is, a pattern that they all declare their relationship to
